The intruder, Jonathan Tran jumped three fences to get onto the grounds and to the door at the South Portico. googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1464204305408-0'); }); 
Tran was able to scale that particular area of the fence without setting off alarms because they had been removed, leading to confusion among officers about his whereabouts and whether an intruder was inside the White House complex, the sources told the Examiner. googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1481811813211-1'); }); 
2. Why didn’t the dogs respond? They appear not to have been on the grounds, because they might ‘hurt someone.’ 
Some agents and officers also are questioning why Secret Service never released the K-9 unit to try to find an intruder after the alarms on the first fence the intruder scaled went off.[…] 
Most of the dogs the Secret Service uses are Belgian Malinois, a breed trained to detect and stop intruders of any kind. The agency is concerned about releasing the dogs too soon and possibly harming people and other animals but they are mostly muzzled so would not do lasting damage if let loose on the South lawn in order to find an intruder, the sources said. 
They also had apparently been limited because of concern that they might hurt former President Barack Obama’s Portuguese water dog, Bo. googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1481811813211-2'); }); 
